05
December
UBA Ghana Rewards / Pins 52 MVPS.
The MD/CEO of UBA Ghana Mr Oliver Alawuba recently hosted 52 Most Valuable Personnel (MVP) for the 2011 financial year at an awards and dinner ceremony held in their honour at his residence in Accra.

The awards celebrants are the inaugural set of MVPs in UBA Ghana. UBA MVP Awards is a Human Resources initiative that rewards role models and consistent performance in the respective functions. The award which reinforces one of UBAs seven key pillars - Employee Involvement and Staff Motivation presented the awardees with a customized 2011 MVP lapel pin and a cash gift as a token of the banks appreciation.

Mr Alawuba elated at the caliber of staff represented at the ceremony, cutting across marketing and operational functions, said that the drive and passion that these few have shown in their commitment to excellence in their roles, is what has taken UBA Ghana to the position of Role Model in Africa

He challenged the MVPs to keep up the drive and aspire to be among the best in 2012. As role models he encouraged them to spur on their peers for the upcoming concluding appraisal for 2012 as well as for future appraisals.

19
September
UBA Ghana Moves 10 Places Up in 2011 Edition of Ghana Club 100
UBA Ghana has moved up 10 places on the prestigious Ghana Club 100 list of companies. After placing 42nd in the 2010 ratings, UBA moved up to the 32nd position in the 2011 ratings leading most of its compatriot institutions from Nigeria in the country.

The well attended Awards Ceremony which was held under the theme; Public Private Partnership-Ensuring Effective Domestic Entrepreneurs Participation in Ghanas Development had companies drawn from the financial, construction, manufacturing and service sector compete for positions on the prestigious listings.

The companies were selected on the basis of their performance in terms of growth, profitability and size.

The annual award is organized by the Ghana Investment Promotion Centre.

UBA Ghana Celebrates National Service Persons
UBA Ghana on Friday August 3,2012 held a send off reception in honour of its National Service Persons who have completed the service period with the bank at the Executive Wing.

In his welcome address the MD/CEO Mr Oliver Alawuba advised the personnel not to relent on their efforts to achieve perfection in their career life. He added that any where they find themselves they should always abide by the tenets of UBAs core values.

The personnel who were very excited received their meritorious certificates after they gave reports on their stewardship.

UBA Pays Tribute To President Mills
The MD/CEO Mr Oliver Alawuba yesterday signed the book of condolence at the Statehouse on behalf of the Board, Management and staff of the bank.

Mr Alawuba in his tribute mentioned that our departed President H.E John Evans Atta Mills was a man of Peace and Humility who loved Christ to the end. The MD/CEO described Fmr. President Mills as a true African. He encouraged all to learn from his exemplary lifestyle.



06
June
UBA Ghana Introduces Cardless ATM Service into the Market

The United Bank for Africa (UBA) Ghana has presented to the public a first of a kind cardless ATM withdrawal service that allows a third party to withdraw cash on its ATM without a card.

The breakthrough innovation in the banking sector was part of three ATM Value Added Services which the bank outdoored to the public, on Tuesday at its Head Office in Accra.

Apart from the cardless ATM withdrawal, the value added services allow customers of the Bank to pay their bills (utility), DSTV subscription fees and also purchase mobile recharge credit on their phone or for third parties.

The Managing Director/CEO, United Bank for Africa, Ghana,
Mr Oliver Alawuba revealed that the addition of the Value Added ATM services is a continuation of the bank’s trail blazing initiatives in the Ghanaian banking industry.

“These newly added services which are powered on the e-Transact platform is aimed at creating a branchless banking which we perceive as the future of banking in Ghana. We see branchless banking as a future of banking in Ghana which therefore means that we must empower customers by providing them several options to access financial services” He added.

Beyond today’s launch UBA has commenced operation of a branchless banking model at the Accra Mall christened the Accra Mall E- Village which is a purely cashless service outlet that provides numerous services such as bill payments and liquidation of funds transfer on cards. I urge all of you gathered here this morning to visit the E-Village and experience the service at the Mall.

Mr George Babafemi, Chief Operating Officer of E-tranzact Ghana lauded UBA for this innovation and advised the general public to fully take advantage of this new and beneficial service.

June
UBA Ghana Impresses at 2011 Banking Awards

UBA Ghana lived up to its billing as one of the top players within the Ghanaian banking landscape at the recently held Banking Awards.

The bank scoped a total of seven awards which was the second highest number of awards won on the night to further manifest its enviable credentials among its peers.

UBA won awards in the following categories:

Winner - Best Bank in Short Term Loan Financing
1st Runner Up Best Bank in Corporate Banking
1st Runner Up Best Bank in Trade Finance
1st Runner Up Best Bank in I. T./ Electronic Banking
1st Runner Up Best Growing Bank
2nd Runner Up Best Bank Medium Term Financing
2nd Runner Up Best Bank in Long Term Financing

According to the MD/CEO, Mr. Oliver Alawuba , these large haul of awards which is the banks largest collection till date is another clear indication of how far the bank has come in terms of providing our cherished customers with the right mix of products and services so as to satisfy their ever increasing needs.

Mr. Alawuba entreated every member of the UBA family to be proud of these awards and the many successes the bank has chalked in the recent past.

He dedicated the awards to our customers for their belief and unflinching support to UBA Ghana and to Staff for their invaluable contributions.

11
April
UBA Ghana Wins Distinguished Achievement Award

The Nigeria High Commission in Ghana last week honoured UBA Ghana with a Distinguished Achievement Award at the La Palm Royal Beach Hotel in Accra Ghana.

The award which coincided with the launching of a book titled: Nigeria Diplomatic Footprint in Ghana; the Obanikoro years welcomed distinguished patrons from the Nigerian social, political, entertainment, business and business communities in Ghana.

His Excellency, Chief Musuliu Obanikoro the outgoing Nigerian High Commission to Ghana, presented an award to UBA which read in recognition of your immense contribution towards the up-liftment of the banner of our great Nation.

Mr Felix Igbinosa, Country Head, Audit & Internal Control who received the award on behalf of the bank, reiterated UBAs commitment towards democratizing banking in Ghana and doing business in Africa.

03
April
UBA Ghana joins top 10 banks in Ghana

The United Bank for Africa (Ghana) Limited (UBA) has joined the top-ten banks in the country in terms of profitability, Mr. Oliver Alawuba, Managing Director/CEO of the bank, has said.

The company’s annual report and financial statements for 2011 show it recorded a profit before tax of GH¢30.2million, against GH¢13.9million in 2010. This represents an increase of 143% over the previous year.

Profit for the year after tax also increased from GH¢9.2million in 2010 to GH¢22.4million.  Deposit volume increased to GH¢404.6million from a previous GH¢311.2million.

A decrease in interest income margins last year presented an opportunity for the bank to go into fees and commissions. About 57% of the bank’s income during the 2011 financial year came from fees and commissions, a trend which would continue, according to Mr. Alawuba.

The bank’s improved risk analysis and prudent measures contributed in reducing its nonperforming loans (NPLs) from 19% in 2010 to 7.91% during the 2011 financial year.

 “We have been able to reduce the bank’s NPLs through our collective effort, and I can say that by the end of the year it will be reduced further to about 5%,” Mr. Alawuba, MD/CEO  told the press.

Commenting on the expectations for the banking industry this year, Mr. Alawuba said: “The operational environment will be different from what pertained last year, because this is an election year. The inflation rate is going down and the margins are coming down as well. These are the realities of 2012.

“In these realities, harsh as it may look, we should be able to use our skills to find a way of doing our business. We will remain focused, and improve our operations and customer service. UBA is also strong in electronic banking, and this will help us serve our customers better and attract new ones.”

He indicated that the bank will support the agricultural sector as part of its measures to diversify its loan distribution for 2012 to include commodities, public-sector business and telecommunications.

The move will see the bank finance commodities such as cocoa, by providing financial assistance to Licenced Buying Companies (LBC) engaged in the purchase of the cash crop as well as farmer associations. The bank further hopes to extend its assistance to shea butter and cotton cultivation.
 
“Fortunately for Ghana, it has a well-established mechanism that is bankable for cocoa. We want to enter that value chain. The cocoa business is well-structured and makes it easier for banks to get into the sector. We will support the LBCs and that will also translate into support for farmers.”

Explaining the rationale for the bank’s decision to go into public finance, Mr. Alawuba said: “For Africa to develop there must be that uniformity of purpose between the private sector and the government in terms of infrastructure development. Most African countries are not doing very well in that regard. The problem is that in time past government did not understand the private sector and vice versa. But it is important that banks assess and help finance some of these critical projects.”

Mr. Alawuba explained that local banks can address the issue of capacity by forming alliances among themselves, and even with foreign banks, to be able to bring in funds to finance some critical public-sector projects.

“UBA has a lot of capacity that it can leverage on, given the number of countries it operates in, to provide some of the critical infrastructure that is needed in the country. UBA has no problem of capacity; the UBA group can support us to undertake big-ticket transactions here in Ghana.”

UBA Ghana Limited is a subsidiary of United Bank for Africa Plc, which is one of Africa’s leading financial institutions offering services to more than 7 million customers across 750 branches and over 2,000 ATMs in 19 African countries.

UBA Ghana has a footprint of 26 fully-networked branches and 40 Visa-enabled ATMs spread across Accra, Tema, Kumasi, Takoradi and Aflao.
 

 

21
March
UBA Ghana hosts Ghana-Italy Investment Forum


UBA Ghana Limited in partnership with Antonveneta and Rdl & Partners this week organized a business seminar to promote investment opportunities between Ghana and Italy.

The serminar had participants drawn from selected Ghanaian businesses, officials from the Ghana Investment Promotion Centre (GIPC) and an Italian delegation led by Frederica Scarzo of Rodl & Partners.

Mr. Oliver Alawuba, MD/CEO in an address mentioned that this initiative is intended to create a platform to foster interaction and collaboration between Ghanaian and Italian companies to explore business opportunities in Ghana and promote Italy as a source of industrial inputs and financing.

Mr. Alawuba espoused UBA Ghanas credentials and the banks preparedness to lend its support to foreign investors who are interested in the many attractive investment opportunities in Ghana.

Miss Scarzo remarked that the partnership with UBA Ghana will go a long way to bring to reality the dreams of many Italian businesses to invest in Ghana. There were presentations from the GIPC, the Italian delegation and a one on one session for participants to engage the Italian businesses.

The participants who were mainly UBA customers expressed their appreciation to UBA Ghana for the unique opportunity presented them.

January
UBA Ghana Celebrates Pioneering Staff

UBA Ghana, on Saturday January 7, 2012 honoured the 24 pioneering staff who are still in bank's employment at the staff end of year party organized to end the 2011 financial year.

The well patronized dinner dance had in attendance staff, a few invited customers and friends of the bank.

The staff were lauded for being part of the unique group of pioneering staff who bought into the vision of creating a truly democratized bank in Ghana in a citation presented to them by the MD/CEO, Oliver Alawuba,   "You have through the year's demonstrated ample proof of your commitment to the continuous development of the bank and have exhibited the banks core values of humility, integrity, empathy and resilience.

On the occasion of our 7th anniversary, United Bank for Africa (Ghana) duly recognizes your immeasurable contribution to the setting up and growth of the bank." The citation concluded.

Rita Mills Robertson on behalf of the pioneers expressed their appreciation to Management for the recognition.

Thank you.
